source: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipes/sweet-and-sour-pork-with-bulgur-wheat-5677d3f04dab71d16a8b4567
course: main course
time required: 30 minutes
cuisine: Asian
nutrition:
  calories: 582 kcal
  fat: 10 g
  saturated fat: 3 g
  carbohydrates: 78 g
  protein: 43 g
servings: 2
---

Bring @water{300%ml} to a boil in a #pot with @vegetable stock pot{1/2}. Pour in the @bulgur wheat{3/4%cup}, place a #lid on the pot and rest off the heat for ~{25%minutes}, or until the water has completely soaked into the wheat.

Meanwhile, peel and dice the @garlic{2%cloves}. Remove the core from the @green pepper{1} and @yellow pepper{1/2} and chop into bite-sized pieces. Thinly slice the @spring onion{2}(thinly sliced), separating the white and green parts.

Cut the @pork medallion{225%g} into bite-sized cubes and season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Spread the @cornflour{1%tbsp} on a #plate and coat the pork thoroughly on all sides.

Turn the hob to high and heat @oil{1%tbsp} in a #frying pan. Line a large #plate with #kitchen paper{}. When the pan is hot, add half the pork and fry until brown (about ~{4%minutes}). Transfer the pork to the lined plate to drain the oil, then fry the remainder.

In a #small bowl{}/#bowl, mix the @Chinese rice vinegar{1%tbsp} with @sugar{1%tbsp} (if you have some). Stir it until the sugar has dissolved then set aside.

Rinse the frying pan used for the pork then put on medium-high heat. Add @oil{1%tbsp} and cook the garlic and the whites of the spring onions for ~{1%minute}. Add the pepper chunks and cook for ~{4%minutes}. Add the @sweet soy sauce{1.5%tbsp} and the vinegar mixture and bring to a simmer.

Return the pork to the #pan and stir thoroughly. Continue cooking for ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper, if needed.

Serve the pork with the bulgur wheat on the side. Sprinkle with the green parts of the spring onions and serve!